article.description:
Vince Carter scored 43 points to
outduel Dwyane Wade as the Nets beat the Heat 90-78 Sunday for New Jersey's12th straight win.
article.headline: Carter outduels Wade as Nets win 12th in a row
article.linkText: Carter outduels Wade as Nets win 12th in a row
article.story:
EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Vince Carter has been the catalyst behind the New Jersey Nets 12-game winning streak.
Chris Sheridan's take

While the Heat grumbled, a few of the Nets, including [Vince] Carter, acknowledged how important it was for them to measure themselves against a team that went 7-0 against them a year ago and swept them from the playoffs.

And then there was [Richard] Jefferson, who seemingly has never heard a premise he didn't disagree with.

"You don't prove yourself until the playoffs."

OK, we'll give Jefferson that.

But to say this victory was no more important than any other would do it a disservice.

To read more of Sunday night's Daily Dime, click here.

Carter, who has averaged 26 points during the streak, scored 33 of his 43 points in the second half to help the Nets overcome Dwyane Wade and the Miami Heat 90-78 on Sunday night. "He's one of the best, and when you're one of the best, you get up for games like this," said Jason Kidd, who added nine points, nine assists and seven rebounds. "When he came here, people talked about how he was soft, how he was a guy who didn't want to compete when things got tough. But we haven't seen that. This is just like last year when he carried us on his back in the second half of the season." Carter had 13 points in a 16-4 run early in the fourth quarter to stave off a Miami rally. It was more than enough to hold off the Heat, who lost their second straight game after winning three in a row. Wade scored 32 points a night after putting up a season-high 44 in a loss to Cleveland. "I'm just trying to do what I can to help this team," said Wade. "We'll get back into it. Other guys will get back into the flow. It's a bump in the road." The Nets squeaked into the playoffs last season largely on the efforts of Carter, who was acquired in a mid-season trade with Toronto. With Kidd ailing and with Richard Jefferson rusty after missing three months with a wrist injury, New Jersey was swept by Miami in the first round of the playoffs. With everyone healthy this season, the Nets (44-28) have won three of four from Miami, though they don't figure to catch the Heat (48-25) for the No. 2 spot in the Eastern Conference behind Detroit. If the three wins have sent a message, no one was letting on. "You don't prove yourself until the playoffs," said Jefferson, who scored 16 points. "Detroit and Miami are the two best teams in the conference, and until someone knocks them off, they're still the two best teams in the conference." Wade was a one-man show for stretches of Sunday's game, but he got little help through the first three quarters when he scored 30 of the Heat's 58 points. Shaquille O'Neal -- playing in his first game since missing two games with a hyperextended left knee -- scored 18 points, nine in the fourth quarter, but Antoine Walker was the only other Miami player in double figures with 11 off the bench. Miami was missing James Posey (ankle tendinitis) and point guard Jason Williams (knee tendinitis). The Heat trailed 74-58 to start the fourth quarter, but scored 11 straight points and trailed just 74-69 when Gary Payton made two free throws with 9:15 left. The Nets missed eight of their first nine shots, but the one they made was a 3-pointer by Carter to break the drought and give them a 77-69 lead. From that point, New Jersey went on a 13-4 run, with Carter providing the final five points with an alley-oop dunk and a 3-pointer to give the Nets a 90-73 lead with 2:35 left. "It was one of those things where you're in a zone," said Carter. "You hit a couple and things are going well and your teammates find you. I was trying to take shots within the flow of the offense. I wasn't trying to force anything." Miami coach Pat Riley sounded a call for help for Wade, who has now led the Heat in scoring in 12 of the team's last 14 games. "We are overloading Dwyane Wade," he said. "We have to go back and get the balance we had for a long period with four or five guys contributing. Not having Jason Williams, a natural point guard that could break down some defenses, really hurts us. We are going to have to revisit some things here."
Game Notes

The Nets won 14 straight games from Jan. 25-Feb. 24, 2004, including 13 after current coach Lawrence Frank took over for Byron Scott. ... Nets C Nenad Krstic had the highlight-reel play of the first half when he found himself leading the pack on a fast break and dunked over Wade, who flew in from behind the 7-footer to attempt the block. ... Sean "P. Diddy" Combs sat at courtside. ... The Nets have held 11 of their last 12 opponents under 90 points.
